# Multi-Target Mirror for `example-infra-repo`

Goal: mirror a single private source repo (`ExampleProject/example-infra-repo`)
to **two or more private target repos in other orgs**, each with its **own**
filter configuration, over a single GitHub Actions workflow.

This generalizes the existing single-target `repo-public-mirror-setup` skill
(private→public, one target) into a multi-target, all-private variant. Every
target is **always filtered** — there is no full/faithful-mirror mode. The
only per-target axis beyond the destination and its filter config is whether
author emails are rewritten (`mailmap=on|off`).

> **Scope note.** This document lives in `global-claude-config` because the
> mirror machinery (the skill, the workflow template) lives here. The work it
> describes targets `ExampleProject/example-infra-repo`, a *different* repository.
> Nothing in `example-infra-repo` is read or modified by writing this doc.
> Implementing the design means creating the workflow and per-target config
> **in that repo**, in a session rooted there.

---

## 1. Why always-filtered, never full

A faithful "push everything" mirror was considered and rejected:

- It would ship `.claude/`, `memory/`, and anything ever committed to history
  verbatim — including any secret that ever landed in a commit. For a source
  like an infra repo that is a real hazard.
- It would include `.github/workflows/`. GitHub deploy keys lack the
  `workflow` OAuth scope, so a push whose diff touches `.github/workflows/`
  is rejected:

  > refusing to allow an OAuth App to create or update workflow … without
  > `workflow` scope

  A faithful mirror over a deploy key therefore cannot work without a PAT or
  GitHub App that carries `workflow` scope — broadening the auth surface for
  no benefit here.

Both problems vanish when every target is filtered: the allowlist excludes
`.github/workflows/` (and anything else not explicitly listed), so per-target
**deploy keys** are sufficient and the auth surface stays minimal. This is the
same reasoning that already governs the public-mirror allowlist (see
`.github/public-mirror/paths.allowlist` in `global-claude-config`, the "Do NOT
add `.github/`" note).

