## 2. The per-target definition model

The source repo holds **one directory per target** under `.github/mirrors/`:

```text
.github/
  mirrors/
    <target-id-1>/
      target.conf        # destination + per-target knobs
      paths.allowlist    # per-target path allowlist
      replacements.txt   # per-target value-scrubbing rules
      mailmap            # present only when mailmap=on
      CONTRIBUTORS.template
    <target-id-2>/
      target.conf
      paths.allowlist
      replacements.txt
      CONTRIBUTORS.template   # mailmap=off here → no mailmap file
  workflows/
    multi-mirror.yml     # one workflow, matrixed over the target dirs
```

`<target-id>` is an arbitrary slug the operator picks (e.g. `acme`,
`partner-eu`). It names the directory, the SSH host alias, the key filename,
and the bookkeeping branches, so it must be unique and shell/ref-safe
(`[a-z0-9-]+`).

### `target.conf` (one per target)

A flat `key = value` file (parsed with a trivial grep/awk in the workflow,
not a YAML dependency):

```ini
# Destination repo (SSH form; can be any org).
url          = git@github.com:OtherOrg/example-infra-mirror.git

# Name of the source-repo Actions secret holding THIS target's
# write-enabled deploy-key private half.
secret       = MIRROR_KEY_ACME

# Rewrite author/committer emails for this target?
#   on  → pass --mailmap (recipients see <localpart>@<domain>.local)
#   off → omit --mailmap (recipients see REAL author identities)
mailmap      = off

# Per-target bookkeeping branch names on the TARGET repo. MUST be
# unique per target — sharing them across targets silently corrupts
# each target's SHA-stability marks.
state_branch = mirror-state-acme
meta_branch  = mirror-meta-acme
```

### `mailmap=on|off` — the only per-target behavior switch

`on` reproduces the public-mirror behavior: `--mailmap` rewrites author and
committer emails to a `<localpart>@<domain>.local` form so real addresses
don't ship. `off` omits the `--mailmap` flag entirely, so the target receives
the **real** author identities — appropriate when the recipients are trusted
people who should see who made each change.

Consequence to document for `mailmap=off` targets (verified from the existing
workflow): the `Regenerate CONTRIBUTORS` step builds the file from
`git shortlog -sne`, which reads whatever emails are in the rewritten history.
With `mailmap=off`, `CONTRIBUTORS` will list the **real** emails. That is
consistent with the intent of an `off` target, but it is a direct consequence
worth stating so nobody is surprised that real addresses appear in
`CONTRIBUTORS` there.

Everything else — `paths.allowlist`, `replacements.txt`, `CONTRIBUTORS`
regeneration, and the `--state-branch` SHA-stability machinery — applies to
every target regardless of the `mailmap` setting.

