## 4. Auth: per-target deploy keys

- Generate **one ed25519 keypair per target repo**, out-of-band
  (`ssh-keygen` — key generation is blocked for the agent by `settings.json`).
  Suggested naming: `~/.ssh/example-mirror-<target>`.
- The **public half** is installed as a **write-enabled deploy key** on each
  target repo: `gh repo deploy-key add <pub> --repo OtherOrg/<repo>
  --title example-multi-mirror --allow-write`. This requires **admin on the
  target repo**, done by whoever administers that org. Cross-org needs **no**
  org-to-org trust relationship — a deploy key is scoped to exactly one repo.
- The **private half** is stored as a distinctly-named Actions secret on the
  **source** repo, matching `target.conf`'s `secret` / the matrix
  `secret_name`: `gh secret set MIRROR_KEY_ACME --repo ExampleProject/example-infra-repo
  < ~/.ssh/example-mirror-acme`.

Why deploy keys and not a PAT/app: narrowest possible scope (write to exactly
one repo, nothing else), no dependency on org membership, and they work
cross-org without any shared identity. The only cost is one key install per
target, which is a one-time admin action on each target repo.

